<TEXT>
a former city council member who helped bring 
the dodgers to los angeles is crying foul over what she says is a 
law firms refusal to play fair with eight baseball season tickets 
rosalind wyman is suing the firm of wyman bautzer kuchel and 
silbert where her husband worked until he died in 1973 
mrs wyman appeared tuesday in los angeles county superior court 
and said the firm gave her use of the tickets in the 1960s and that 
she signed an agreement when her husband died that gave her right 
of first refusal of the tickets and the right to buy them if the 
firm didnt 
mrs wyman contends the firm gave away two of the tickets and 
failed to give her access to the rest 
law firm spokesman charles stern said he had not seen a copy of 
the complaint but added i was dismayed she felt she had to sue 
since i had been negotiating with her and her attorneys for many 
weeks and we were very close to an arrangement that would have made 
everybody happy 
theres principle involved said mrs wyman who served on 
the city council from 1953 to 1965 and was instrumental in the 
dodgers move from brooklyn in 1958 at 22 she was the youngest 
person ever elected to the council 
one of my biggest and longest and most involved fights was to 
bring a major league baseball team to this city as an elected 
official i really feel i made a contribution to my community 
the dodgers are in first place in the national league west 2 
games ahead of san francisco 
</TEXT>
