<TEXT>
as birds learn to sing their bodies create new 
brain cells that indirectly link up to nerves controlling vocal 
muscles scientists reported today 
a major portion of the vocal motor nerve pathway is actually 
created during song learning researchers wrote in the british 
journal nature 
previous studies have found that adult canaries create cells in 
a portion of the brain involved in controlling songs the new work 
strengthens the case that such growth in birds plays a role in song 
learning said an editorial accompanying the new report 
in the study kathy and ernest nordeen of the university of 
rochester in new york studied brains of male zebra finches the 
birds memorize song between 20 and 65 days after hatching and 
start practicing at about 30 days of age 
the researchers identified brain cells that arose between ages 
of 20 days and 64 days in a part of the brain critical for song 
production more than half the new cells reached into a second area 
of the brain that in turn projects to nerve cells that control 
vocal muscles they report 
males beyond the learning period and young females which do not 
sing create far fewer extra brain cells in the critical part of 
the brain researchers said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

