<TEXT>
a fight over dutyfree ethanol imports from 
caribbean refineries is one of the fights flaring up as the house 
readies for yet another round in the battle over trade legislation 
its a sweetheart arrangement for a few select companies 
house minority leader robert h michel rill declared tuesday as 
he opened fire on the ethanol provision in the 1000page trade 
bill 
the bill is set to come to the house floor for a vote today 
president reagan vetoed a slightly different version of the bill 
on may 24 he cited provisions that would limit alaska oil exports 
and require companies to provide employees with 60day notice of 
plant closings and largescale layoffs 
within hours of reagans veto the house voted to pass the 
legislation and make it law in spite of his objections but the 
senate fell short of the twothirds required for a veto override in 
a june 8 vote 
the alaska oil and plantclosings provisions have been dropped 
from the version of the bill now coming to the floor sponsors say 
reagan might be more willing to accept the measure in its modified 
form 
i strongly believe congress owes it to the american people to 
do all we can to enact a trade policy house ways and means 
committee chairman dan rostenkowski dill said 
reagan however also was critical of the ethanol provision in 
his veto message the plan was conceived as a way to expand 
benefits under reagans caribbean basin initiative but critics say 
it goes too far 
ethanol or ethyl alcohol is used for fuel and can be refined 
from a variety of farm products us corn growers have been irate 
over the trade bills provision to open the door to dutyfree 
imports 
michel said it would not only hurt corn growers but take away 
refining jobs in the united states and abuse the caribbean basin 
initiative he said the initiative was designed to boost industries 
native to the caribbean but that five companies currently are using 
island refineries to convert european products into ethanol 
for example michel said spanish wine has been shipped to the 
caribbean and refined into the alcohol fuel 
meanwhile the plantclosings provision is moving through 
congress as a separate piece of legislation or almost separate 
the house is acting under a format requiring a vote first on the 
plantclosings bill followed quickly by action on the trade 
measure labor officials were uneasy over splitting off the 
plantclosings issue in the first place they went along with the 
idea after democratic leaders agreed to place it first in line 
ahead of trade 
the plantclosings bill already passed by the senate will go 
to the presidents desk if as expected it wins house approval 
exactly what lies in store for the trade bill remains unclear 
house approval would send it to the senate which already has 
another version of the measure on its calendar and where numerous 
amendments await it 
little time remains to sort out the amendments many highly 
controversial before lawmakers leave washington for the campaign 
trail 
and there is a question about how much appetite the senate will 
have for the painful nittygritty of committee action on trade with 
the bills sponsor sen lloyd bentsen dtexas increasingly torn 
away by his responsibilities as gov michael dukakis running mate 
the central provisions of the bill would overhaul the system 
under which the united states imposes import curbs to protect 
american industries and retaliates against international trade 
violations by other countries 
the measure also contains a wide array of other provisions 
ranging from repeal of the 1980 windfall profits tax on oil 
companies to more than 2 billion in agricultural subsidies 
