the pentagon is likely to propose closing 20 
to 25 major military installations if congress finally approves a 
plan to permit the elimination of unneeded bases a key congressman 
says 
that seems to be about the number that have been recommended 
in the past rep les aspin dwis chairman of the house armed 
services committee said as the house voted overwhelming approval 
of the complicated plan 
the 37439 vote by the house late tuesday afternoon sends the 
plan to a housesenate conference committee to be reconciled with a 
senate measure approved two months ago 
while the congressional negotiators are working out the legal 
details a bipartisan ninemember commission appointed by defense 
secretary frank c carlucci is already at work trying to come up 
with a list of unneeded bases 
the commission is headed by former sen abe ribicoff dconn 
and former rep jack edwards rala 
carlucci has estimated that between 2 billion and 5 billion a 
year could be saved if unneeded bases were closed 
but congress worried about the loss of jobs has blocked the 
pentagon from closing any major bases since 1977 the commission 
plan was developed as a way to take congress off the hook and it 
is strongly supported by the reagan administration 
the commission is supposed to make its recommendations by dec 
31 president reagan would then have until jan 16 four days 
before he leaves office to accept or reject the entire list he 
could not approve a partial list 
if reagan approved the list the action could be blocked only by 
a majority vote of both the house and senate the closings would 
begin after jan 1 1990 
the pentagon has about 3800 installations in the united states 
but only 355 are major bases that employ more than 300 civilians 
aspin said he said the 20 to 25 bases to be closed would come from 
among that list of 355 
aspin said his figure is based on the historical record he 
noted that the pentagon in 1985 had proposed shutting 22 bases 
after world war ii the pentagon generally was permitted to do 
what it wanted with bases with the exception of a handful 
protected by key members of congress the pentagon closed 3600 
installations between 1961 and 1977 
but things changed after 1975 when the air force proposed 
shutting down loring air force base in northern maine that states 
legislators blocked the move by requiring lengthy and costly 
environmental impact studies for the loring closing and all future 
closings 
the chief author of the baseclosing plan rep dick armey 
rtexas said the vote will go a long way toward cutting fat 
instead of muscle from our national defense 
armeys plan was rejected in 1987 by a 199192 vote but he 
offered the proposal again because he argued that a lameduck 
