<TEXT>
defense secretary frank c carlucci is urging 
defense contractors to rein in their private consultants but says 
his job is not to punish companies in the pentagon bribery 
probe 
carlucci appeared before the senate armed services committee on 
tuesday to explain his decision to rescind contract payment 
suspensions he had imposed july 1 on nine defense contractors 
carlucci said a navy review showed the contracts hadnt been 
tainted as he had feared when he acted on the basis of fbi 
affidavits outlining alleged trading in inside pentagon contracting 
information 
my job is not to punish companies my job is to protect the 
national security carlucci said noting that its up to the 
justice department to prosecute alleged legal violations 
but he added if other official information becomes available 
during the course of the investigation which warrants new concern 
regarding these or other contracts the department will evaluate it 
and take any appropriate action 
carlucci characterized the suspensions as a warning and said 
he is writing the heads of the nations top 200 defense contractors 
to urge them to ensure stringent management controls on the use 
of consultants to avoid improper business practices 
the investigation focuses on allegations that defense 
contractors and their consultants bribed pentagon officials for 
inside information that could have been vital in bidding for 
contracts worth billions of dollars no charges have yet been filed 
carlucci has appointed a task force to look at the complicated 
weapons procurement process and recommend any needed changes he 
urged congress to let that panel do its job hasty or piecemeal 
reforms could do more harm than good he said 
in addition some of the wrongdoing being uncovered may simply 
be violations of the law not system deficiencies he said 
but he admitted there are problems that need to be fixed 
there are defects in how america equips its forces 
one of those he noted is what i would term intervention 
points opportunities for friendships or political clout to carry 
more weight than contractor performance or product quality and 
cost 
we can reduce these opportunities for intervention through 
such techniques as longterm contracts simplifying specifications 
freezing weapons designs contracting to performance and 
multiyear approvals of programs he said 
while carlucci was promising more reviews of contracts the 
justice department is weighing a request from some defense lawyers 
to investigate the source of leaks to the press 
john russell a department spokesman said officials are looking 
at the letter sent july 8 to michael e shaheen jr head of the 
justice departments office of professional responsibility 
the letter signed by 16 attorneys for people and companies in 
the defense probe said we are writing to you to request that 
you commence an investigation and take appropriate remedial action 
to deal with the virtual flood of leaks by department of justice 
employees involved in or privy to the details of the 
investigation 
russell said it was too early to determine that we will 
undertake an investigation shaheen who has responsibility for 
investigating ethics cases involving justice employees refused to 
comment 
investigations into leaks are not unusual russell said at 
one time we have anywhere from 10 to 15 leak investigations going 
on he said some of those include improper revelations of 
classified material 
the letter claims the frequency and substance of these news 
leaks have been unprecedented and are unfair to the people whose 
names have surfaced in the investigation 
the letter outlined seven statutes regulations or rules that 
bar justice employees from revealing unauthorized material one law 
carries a fine of up to 1000 and imprisonment of a year for 
divulging certain material other penalties can include a letter of 
censure or dismissal 
henry e hudson the us attorney in alexandria va who is 
coordinating the massive probe has also expressed concern about 
leaks in the case which was brought to public attention june 14 
fbi agents conducted surprise searches on more than three dozen 
homes and offices in 12 states that day 
