<TEXT>
the chairman of a house subcommittee is 
accusing the securities and exchange commission of yielding to 
pressure from the brokerage industry over a proposal to widen the 
choices investors have in disputes with brokers 
rep edward markey dmass chairman of the house 
telecommunications and finance subcommittee told sec chairman 
david s ruder on tuesday that his agency apparently suffered a 
failure of nerve after receiving a firestorm of criticism from 
industry lobbyists 
last month the sec considered proposing a bill that would have 
allowed the agency to ban contracts that bind investors to 
arbitration instead of going to court 
clauses that require binding arbitration are standard in many 
brokerage contracts they have been under scrutiny since the 
october stock market crash which generated thousands of complaints 
by investors claiming they had been treated poorly by brokers 
the commission decided against submitting such legislation 
instead at its july 7 meeting the sec voted to ask the exchanges 
to study the issue and report by oct 15 
markey complained to ruder who was appearing before the 
telecommunications panel that the brokerage industry has had 
numerous contacts with the sec in recent weeks to complain about 
efforts to rein in arbitration 
im sure these visitors spoke with one voice in a chorus of 
opposition to any interference with their right to impose 
arbitration clauses on investors markey said 
a bill was introduced last week by rep rick boucher dva 
that would forbid brokers from requiring that their customers agree 
to binding arbitration it also would require that brokers make 
investors aware of arbitration clauses in contracts and alter some 
arbitration procedures such as requiring written decisions 
ruder however said such legislation seems unnecessary he said 
many brokerage companies have told the sec in recent weeks that 
they have abandoned plans to include the arbitration clauses in 
their contracts 
i think where the industry is going has changed ruder said 
ruder told the lawmakers that congress should hold off action 
until oct 15 when the nations stock exchanges have been asked to 
offer suggestions on the matter 
markey and others pointed out that congress is scheduled to 
adjourn for the year in early october that would mean if lawmakers 
were to withhold legislation until the industry offers its 
suggestions congress could not act until next year 
the brokerage industry has argued that arbitration is a quick 
relatively inexpensive way of resolving disputes between investors 
and brokers critics however have argued that investors often 
dont realize they are agreeing to limit themselves to arbitration 
and should not be denied an opportunity to go to court 
