<TEXT>
irans attempts this week to elicit 
international condemnation of the downing of iran air flight 655 
could also give us officials a chance to demand answers to 
several puzzles that only iran can provide 
iran is taking the us downing of its airliner onto the 
international stage beginning today in hopes of bringing worldwide 
pressure to bear on the united states to withdraw its naval forces 
from the persian gulf 
but in going before the international civil aviation 
organization today and the un security council on thursday iran 
may also give the united states a chance to demand answers from 
tehran on several key questions 
chief among them are whether the airliner was indeed 
broadcasting some of its identification signals on a military 
channel and if so why 
meanwhile in the persian gulf rear adm william fogarty is 
heading the us investigation to determine why the sophisticated 
radar and tracking system aboard the vincennes mistook the a300 
airbus for an f14 fighter and to determine how the ships 
skipper capt will c rogers iii reached his decision to fire 
defense secretary frank c carlucci testifying before the 
senate armed services committee said tuesday the investigation 
will take at least another two weeks to complete fogarty 
originally was given 15 days after the july 3 incident to finish 
his report with an option to extend 
here are some of the questions the us investigators will 
address and the answers in many cases only partial that have 
been suggested so far 
q why did vincennes believe the airbus was an f14 
a pentagon spokesman dan howard has said the most compelling 
reason was that the airbus was broadcasting two identification 
signals one using a frequency and a code used by both civilian and 
military aircraft the other using a frequency used only by 
military aircraft and a code associated with iranian f14s 
investigators are looking for further confirmation of the two 
signals if the signals were sent iran has not explained why 
q did the vincennes officers realize a commercial aircraft was 
due in the area 
a officers in the wardroom of the vincennes thumbed frantically 
through a commercial schedule but did not see flight 655 from 
bandar abbas to dubai howard said that the plane was 27 minutes 
off schedule and fourandahalf miles off the center of a 
commercial air corridor iran says it recognizes an air corridor 20 
miles wide and that in any case the plane was within the 
ninemilewide corridor recognized by other nations 
q do f14s pose a special threat 
a us commanders in the gulf were on heightened alert over 
that weekend in part because they had received intelligence 
reports from multiple sources that you can expect a fourth of 
july surprise according to an official familiar with the 
incident 
additionally iran recently moved several of its estimated 15 
f14 fighters to bandar abbas the f14 the most sophisticated 
iranian plane has been used sparingly in combat although one did 
shoot down an iraqi f1 last february for the most part iran uses 
the sophisticated radar system aboard the f14 to spot possible 
iraqi air attacks against tankers carrying iranian oil through the 
gulf according to pentagon and congressional sources 
q iranian officials say that flight 655 had been in radio 
contact with air traffic control although it is not clear whether 
this was before or after it took off did american forces overhear 
such communications 
a the investigation will reveal whether us listening posts 
monitored such radio broadcasts say pentagon spokesmen but the 
vincennes did not hear the broadcasts howard said such broadcasts 
are made on vhf wavelengths which are best received within sight of 
the transmitter said one pentagon expert if a us surveillance 
aircraft had been aloft it might have overheard transmissions from 
the iran flight while it was on the ground 
