<TEXT>
here is a thumbnail sketch of dick thornburgh 
nominated by president reagan to succeed edwin meese iii as 
attorney general 
age 55 
family the son of an engineer and grandson of a university 
professor thornburgh is married to the former virginia judson a 
schoolteacher his first wife also named virginia was killed in 
an automobile accident in 1960 that left the youngest of his three 
sons brain damaged thornburgh now has a fourth son by his second 
wife whom he married in 1963 
education he earned a civil engineering degree from yale 
university in 1954 he returned to his native pittsburgh and earned 
a law degree from the university of pittsburgh law school in 1957 
job history he was appointed us attorney for western 
pennsylvania in 1969 as a prosecutor his targets included a us 
customs agent a county sheriff and a former gop congressman j 
irving whalley who was convicted in a kickback case in 1975 he 
was appointed by president ford to be assistant attorney general in 
charge of the justice departments criminal division 
in 1978 the republican thornburgh defeated former pittsburgh 
mayor pete flaherty for governor he ran on a platform of cleaning 
up corruption in the democratic administration of thengov milton 
shapp a democrat he was reelected in 1982 narrowly defeating 
former congressman allen ertel during a recession that made it 
difficult for incumbent gop candidates 
barred by law from seeking a third term thornburgh left 
pennsylvania at the end of 1986 to head the institute of politics 
at harvard universitys kennedy school of government 
positions as governor thornburghs budget proposals held 
spending increases to less than the rate of inflation for eight 
straight years he championed a controversial welfare reform law 
that limited cash benefits to three months a year for an estimated 
68000 people considered ablebodied 
a sampling of his positions 
on abortion thornburgh has a mixed record in december 1981 
he vetoed an abortion control act saying he objected to sections 
that said life started at conception that mandated a 24hour 
waiting period and that would have established criminal penalties 
for doctors who broke the law 
on june 11 1982 however thornburgh signed a watereddown 
version of the abortion bill which required doctors to notify 
women about the risks of abortion and the availability of medical 
assistance for prenatal care and childbirth portions of the law 
were later struck down by the us supreme court 
on capital punishment thornburgh said during both terms in 
office that he favored the death penalty for certain murders and 
for persons convicted of killing police officers and prison guards 
during his first term the death penalty was reinstated in 
pennsylvania during his second term thornburgh signed warrants 
setting execution dates for several convicted murderers appeals 
courts granted stays in each case 
on gun control thornburgh said while campaigning for his first 
term that he opposed further government regulation of the sale or 
purchase of firearms subsequent public statements on this issue 
could not be found while governor thornburgh signed a bill 
setting a mandatory fiveyear sentence for any person convicted of 
using a gun during a crime 
on drugs thornburgh expanded funding and staffing for the 
state police and created special units to investigate drug 
trafficking and organized crime he also supported efforts to 
provide tougher prison sentences for some drugrelated crimes 
