<TEXT>
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers 
throughout the nation 
 
july 8 
the morning news tribune tacoma wash on the shooting down of 
an iranian airliner 
the investigation into the destruction of an iranian airliner 
seems headed toward two conclusions one is that there was no 
deliberate provocation on the part of the iranian government iran 
air flight 655 was within a recognized commercial flight corridor 
when it was shot down by the uss vincennes 
the second conclusion is that capt william c rogers apparently 
acted responsibly when he loosed two antiaircraft missiles against 
the approaching jet like other us commanders in the persian 
gulf rogers was under orders not to risk the kind of air attack 
that killed 37 sailors aboard the uss stark last year 
the two conclusions lead inescapably to a third if neither the 
pilot nor the skipper was at fault in the tragedy then the fault 
must lie with the decisions in washington dc that placed both 
the vincennes and the airliner at such extreme and unavoidable risk 
this disaster exposes the flaws of americas persian gulf 
policy in theory the us navy is acting as a neutral protector 
of international shipping threatened by the war between iran and 
iraq 
constantly under threat these warships are confined to a narrow 
body of water that provides little advance warning of approaching 
jets they have weapons that can destroy a plane long before it can 
be positively identified their nervous crews must instantly 
distinguish the occasional hitandrun attack from the constant 
traffic of civilian ships and aircraft 
its time to rethink the whole policy before this risky naval 
posture becomes institutionalized 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 12 
topeka kan capitaljournal on the suggestion to divert water 
from the great lakes to the mississippi 
a proposal by a group of southern senators to increase the 
discharge from the great lakes to assist navigation on the 
mississippi river is reasonable a 100day increase in water 
release would lower the level of lakes huron and michigan by about 
an inch and increase the river level by about a foot at st louis 
and six inches at memphis 
the increased flow would greatly ease the barge traffic on the 
mississippi save thousands of hours of work in dredging channels 
in the river and lower the cost of transporting the nations grain 
crops to ports on the gulf of mexico 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 12 
central maine morning sentinel waterville maine on closing 
unneeded military bases 
if you believe theres waste in the defense budget dont blame 
it all on the generals and the admirals or even the defense 
contract influence peddlers 
as walt kellys pogo might have put it the villain may be us 
the pentagon could save millions by closing down obsolete bases 
but every time it tries it is blocked by congress which fears the 
anger of voters in districts where bases are located 
thats why the closings can be accomplished only by the adoption 
of a politically neutral plan such as that proposed by rep dick 
armey a texas republican it would protect members from angry 
constituents by setting up a bipartisan commission to recommend 
which bases should be closed the secretary of defense would be 
authorized to close all or none he couldnt pick and choose that 
way there would be no room for political favoritism the whole plan 
would have to play out between election day in november and 
inauguration day in january thus taking the issue as far as 
possible out of politics 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 11 
las cruces nm sunnews on the closing military bases 
congress has once again avoided one of the more sensitive issues 
it has had to face closing military bases the pentagon says are 
obsolete 
late last week the house tossed around the issue during a 
fourhour debate all the members could agree on was to postpone 
any final decision 
difficult or not its impossible to talk about cutting defense 
spending without talking about cutting back somewhere 
the united states faces the largest debt in its history it just 
seems to make sense to cut back in areas like the bases that have 
outlived their usefulness 
in the long run closing installations that no longer serve any 
purpose may be a positive step toward cutting defense spending at a 
point where it will do the least harm to our national security 
</TEXT>
