the chattanooga tenn times on congressional pay raises 
how much is your congressman or senator worth opinions vary 
but each year congress has a battle over whether to raise its 
salary 
recently the house voted a 4 percent increase for federal 
employees but exempted members of congress and other top officials 
now rep dan rostenkowski dill has come up with a plan that 
seems daffy but could be valuable members of congress would be 
able to choose a salary between the current 89500 and the 
135000 last recommended by the federal pay commission but could 
not keep any honoraria for speeches to trade associations and other 
groups 
voters would decide in the next election whether the congressman 
is worth it rep rostenkowski thinks the plan would eliminate much 
of the hypocrisy that accompanies the annual debate over salaries 
especially when votes are called on pay increases 
some congressmen are underpaid and others are overpaid the 
rostenkowski plan would let members judge the value of their 
service and then a few months thereafter allow constituents to 
cast the judgment that really counts makes sense to us 
