<TEXT>
a 40ton rocket carrying a research 
satellite plunged into the sea minutes after takeoff wednesday 
scientists said it was indias second launch failure in 15 months 
the rockets firststage motor apparently malfuctioned shortly 
after the rocket the augmented satellite launch vehicle aslv 
blasted off at 228 pm from sriharikota island 1100 miles 
southeast of new delhi according to a scientist at the launch site 
the scientist who spoke on condition of anomymity said contact 
with the rocket was lost 1 minute and 15 seconds after takeoff the 
united news of india news agency said the rocket crashed into the 
indian ocean 4 minutes and 10 seconds after the launch 
the chairman of the indian space research organization in new 
delhi ur rao was quoted as saying the exact cause of the launch 
failure had not been determined 
it was the second failed indian space mission since another 
rocket from the same aslv series plunged into the bay of bengal in 
march 1987 when its firststage motor failed to ignite minutes 
after launching 
the scientist at the launch site said the firststage motor in 
wednesdays launch ignited but something went wrong after that 
the rocket carried a 330pound satellite designed to take 
threedimensional photographs of earth and conduct experiments on 
the origins of gamma rays the satellite was to enter an orbit 240 
miles above earth scientists said 
the failure of the mission comes amid reports that india could 
develop the aslv rocket as a launch vehicle for nuclear weapons 
according to anthony h cordesman a us military analyst the 
rocket with the addition of a heat shield and a guidance system 
could deploy intermediaterange ballistic missiles or irbm 
the indians themselves have estimated that they could have an 
operational nucleararmed irbm by 1989 cordesman said in a 
published report 
india exploded an atomic device in 1974 but the government says 
its nuclear program is for peaceful purposes 
