<TEXT>
an increase in the suns activity early in the 
1990s will thin out the 7000 pieces of manmade space junk orbiting 
near earth a congressional subcommittee was told wednesday 
but there was a warning too that nations with space programs 
had better clean up their act 
nicholas l johnson an expert in space debris said the 
socalled solar maximum will present a unique opportunity to 
affect noticeably the safety of future space travelers because 
it will substantially cleanse the environment below 400 miles 
altitude 
the solar maximum a phenomenon that last occurred in 1980 is 
expected to be above average in intensity when it peaks in 1990 
its effect is to heat the atmosphere and cause it to expand 
causing a wider area of debris to plunge toward earth and burn up 
during the mid1990s two great space stations one built by 
nasa and its international partners and one constructed by the 
soviet union will be deployed at altitudes near 300 miles said 
johnson an advisory scientist with teledyne brown engineering in 
colorado 
actions taken by the us space industry and government and by 
other foreign space users can ensure that we do not unnecessarily 
repopulate the region of nearearth space below 500 miles 
johnson and others testified before the house space science 
subcommittee the panels chairman rep bill nelson dfla said 
we have to figure out what to do about this problem before we 
have a catastrophe 
on a table in the hearing room were samples of objects that had 
been in space and were hit by manmade debris one piece was a 
section of a space shuttle window gouged by a paint flake from a 
spent delta rocket 
johnson said debris does not pose a serious hazard to space 
operations now but might when space activities increase in the next 
decade 
the national aeronautics and space administration already is 
adding 12000 pounds of protective shielding to the proposed space 
station 
today more than 7000 objects with a diameter of 10 
centimeters 4 inches or more are known to be in orbit about our 
planet said johnson at collision velocities of 8 to 10 
kilometers per second these satellites carry explosivelike 
energy 
donald kessler a debris expert at nasas johnson space center 
in houston estimated that five times as many pieces of manmade 
junk are in orbit near the earth than can be tracked by radar 
the experts said only 5 percent of the identified objects 
spinning around earth represent operational satellites fully half 
come from satellites that exploded either deliberately or 
accidentally 
since the first known satellite breakup in june 1961 johnson 
said nearly 100 satellites have broken up in orbit with debris 
spreading out and encircling most of the globe 
onethird of the debris is spent rocket bodies and dead 
payloads he said 
the rest is operational debris objects intentionally discarded 
during satellite delivery they include such things as lens caps 
empty propellant tanks or objects thrown away or dropped outside a 
spacecraft during manned activity 
