here is a transcript of michael dukakis 
speech wednesday to the convention of the national association for 
the advancement of colored people 
thank you dr hooks ben how would you like to start traveling 
with me all over america thanks very very much to all of you and 
a special thanks to dr hooks dr gibson and the good people who 
met with me in boston last week we had a good meeting and i hope 
its the first of many many meetings not just in the campaign 
but in the transition and in the white house itself that doors 
going to be open and were going to be working together were 
going to be listening to each other yes ben ive learned a lot 
from jesse and ive learned a lot from you and i continue to 
learn and thats going to continue and grow stronger and stronger 
as time goes on 
may i make just a few very special introductions if i can 
first im very proud today to be with the woman who has been my 
lifes partner for over a quarter of a century i want you all to 
know that our dear son informed us just the other day that despite 
our youth were going to be grandparents in january the babys 
due to arrive between the 18th and the 31st of january 1989 with 
your help its going to be quite a january ladies and gentlemen 
the first lady of the commonwealth of massachusetts shes going 
to be a great first lady of the united states of america kitty 
dukakis im going to save the second introduction for the end of 
my speech 
in 1954 a young man from massachusetts who was then a senior at 
swarthmore college a small coeducational school as many of you 
know just outside of philadelphia came to this city as a student 
in the washington semester program at american university those 
were difficult and troubled times they were a time when this city 
was a segregated city and it was our capital city it was the fall 
of 1954 when a senator from wisconsin named joseph r mccarthy was 
being censured by the united states senate im not sure i could 
have possibly believed that fall of 1954 in this capital city of 
ours that i would be here today in front of this great 
organization that has given so much to this country and has so much 
more to give now and in the future speaking to you as a candidate 
for the presidency of the united states 
dr hooks said something which i want to repeat it would have 
been inconceivable as all of you and and all of us know in 1954 
or for that matter in 1984 that the two leading and final 
candidates for the democratic nomination for the presidency of the 
united states would be this son of greek immigrants from 
massachusetts and a black man who grew up poor in south carolina 
ladies and gentlemen it happened and it happened in the 
democratic party im proud of that im proud of that im proud 
of the fact that it was my party that has opened up the door of 
opportunity to all of our citizens and im proud of the fact that 
im here today with kitty with senator and mrs bentsen and with 
all of you 
im not sure when we met a year ago in new york city that 
evening when so many of you were good enough to stick around when 
i was late and i had just arrived im not sure i could possibly 
have imagined even then that i would be here today and im sure i 
dont have to tell any of you how seriously i take the 
responsibilities of the presidency the responsibilities of 
leadership the responsibility to be a president of all the people 
and that is what i want to talk to you about for just a few minutes 
this morning 
twentynine years ago right here in washington dc dr 
martin luther king jr concluded his remarks to a gathering of some 
26000 high school and college students with these words he said 
make a career of humanity make a career of humanity commit 
yourself to the noble struggle for equal rights and you will make 
a greater person of yourself a greater nation of your country and 
a finer world in which to live make a career of humanity thats 
what dr martin luther king said that day 
i dont know if any of you were there that day to hear him 
speak but i do know that im proud to be here this morning because 
the naacp has made a career of humanity has made a career of 
humanity from roy wilkins courageous fight for antilynching laws 
in the 1930s to the civil rights movement of the 1950s and 60s to 
the battle we all wage today to bring down the barriers of 
opportunity to citizens in this country your leadership in 
communities all over america has made this a better and a greater 
nation and i commend you for it and im proud and honored to be 
here today as your guest 
</TEXT>
