<TEXT>
here is a chronology of recent usnicaraguan relations 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 17 anastasio somoza nicaraguan president resigns and 
ends more than four decades of rightist proamerican rule by his 
family two days later leftist sandinista rebels enter managua 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
reports emerge alleging covert us aid to antisandinista rebel 
contras nicaragua claims violations of its territory by us spy 
planes and warships 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april congressional sources say cia is involved in military 
action against sandinista government by supervising mining of 
nicaraguan ports nicaragua files complaint at world court against 
united states charging us efforts to coerce and intimidate 
nicaragua through support of contra forces 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may 1 president reagan announces trade embargo against 
nicaragua 
august enactment of foreignaid bill resuming direct aid to 
contras 27 million in nonlethal assistance 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 25 after intensive lobbying by reagan house approves 
100 million in military and humanitarian aid to contras senate 
approves package two months later 
june 27 world court denounces ussponsored military actions 
against nicaragua and us support for contras as violation of un 
charters ban on use of force 
oct 5 military cargo plane is shot down in nicaragua killing 
two americans surviving crew member eugene hasenfus is captured 
and implicates cia in contrasupply operation hasenfus released 
two months later 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
feb 18 senate foreign relations committee votes narrowly to 
halt us aid to contras 
aug 7 five central american presidents sign peace plan 
calling for ceasefires and additional steps toward democratization 
in effort to end guerrilla wars in nicaragua and elsewhere in 
region 
dec 3 indirect talks between sandinista government and 
contras begin 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january responding to pressure from other central american 
nations sandinistas agree to direct talks with contras nicaragua 
lifts 6yearold state of emergency and begins facetoface 
negotiations with contras 
mar 17 us troops arrive in honduras as show of force 
against nicaragua whose forces reportedly have crossed honduran 
border in offensive against contra rebels 
mar 23 sandinista leaders and contra representatives announce 
ceasefire plan that would end war by may 31 
may 31 after several runds of talks that fail to produce any 
agreement the truce ends ceasefire extensions are announced 
june 9 in the latest breakoff of negotiations contras reject 
a sandinista plan both sides report numerous violations of 
ceasefire in following weeks 
july 11 nicaragua orders expulsion of us ambassador and 
seven other diplomats one day after police clash with thousands of 
demonstraters at antisandinista rally government closes down 
opposition newspaper la prensa and catholic radio station 
july 12 us retaliates ordering nicaraguan ambassador and 
seven others out 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

