<TEXT>
the governing nationalist party ended a 
weeklong congress wednesday after removing many older leaders from 
the chiang kaishek era and promising to expand contacts with china 
delegates to the 13th nationalist congress elected president lee 
tenghui as party chairman the first native taiwanese to hold the 
post 
they also replaced threefifths of the partys central committee 
with new members whose average age dropped from 70 to 59 
the nationalist party or kuomintang has exercised oneparty 
rule in taiwan since 1949 when chiang kaishek and his followers 
fled from mainland china after losing a civil war to the communists 
premier yu kuohwa a 74yearold member of the old guard who 
heads the cabinet was chosen 35th among 360 candidates for the 
180member central committee 
yu viewed as the most powerful holdover from the chiang 
kaishek era received fewer votes than many younger taiwanborn 
candidates 
for the first time in the partys 94year history many 
delegates were not handpicked by nationalist officials 
but the extent of the changes in leadership will not be clear 
until the new members of the central standing committee the 
policymaking organ of the party are named thursday a cabinet 
reshuffle also is expected soon 
taiwans economic prosperity in recent years has increased the 
pressure for democratization before he died in january president 
chiang chingkuo eldest son of chiang kaishek lifted martial law 
and the ban on opposition parties 
the pace of further liberalization however will depend on the 
personnel changes in the cabinet and central standing committee 
the congress has demonstrated that our party delegates can 
reflect public opinion and are full of vitality said lee 
shengfung a reformminded nationalist legislator 
but we are not certain of our new leadership yet he said 
i hope we can have a new leadership that can keep the social 
trend in its grasp and make good use of this vitality 
native taiwanese representation in the newlychosen central 
committee increased from 17 percent to about 40 percent about 85 
percent of the islands nearly 20 million people are native 
taiwanese ethnic chinese whose families lived in taiwan before 
the nationalists arrived from the mainland 
lee closed the congress in suburban taipei by reiterating his 
partys traditional claim to have the sole right to govern china 
he also emphasized taiwans policy never to negotiate with the 
communist government in beijing 
but the nationalists onceresolute policy of having no contacts 
with china continued to crumble at the congress 
chiang chingkuo last october ended a ban on travel to the 
mainland for family reunions and more than 100000 taiwan 
residents have since made the trip 
the nationalists also eased a ban on visits to taiwan by 
mainland china residents under the new policy the chinese can 
come to the island if close relatives are ill or have died some 
intellectuals and students also will be permitted to visit 
in addition the nationalists say they want to extend taiwans 
economic contacts with china although all business activity must 
be negotiated through third parties 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

