socialist premier michel rocards government 
approved two bills wednesday that would tax the rich to guarantee 
the poor a minimum income 
the solidarity wealth tax would take between 05 percent and 
09 percent annually from someones net worth if it exceeds four 
million francs about 645000 the tax would finance a guaranteed 
minimum income for citizens and foreign residents without means 
this tax is explained by the need for the most favored people 
to perhaps participate more than others in this effort of 
solidarity said government spokesman claude evin who also is 
minister of solidarity health and social protection 
the bills approved by the cabinet will go to the national 
assembly during its autumn session they were among the top 
priorities set by president francois mitterrand in his successful 
campaign for election earlier this year 
a controversial wealth tax imposed by a socialist government in 
1982 prompted some french citizens to move large portions of their 
money out of the country that tax assessed on worth of three 
million francs or more was abolished in 1986 when the conservative 
government of premier jacques chirac came to power for two years 
about 110000 households would be affected by the new tax the 
same number as previously but the tax rates are lower than in the 
previous case exemptions are nearly identical including 
familyowned businesses art works and forest land 
the tax is expected to produce about 645 million a year to help 
about 500000 people who would have to agree to take part in 
jobsearech programs individuals would get the equivalent of at 
least 323 a month to live on and couples would get 484 
