<TEXT>
drought and burning heat have already squeezed 
livestock producers and could hurt them further if conditions 
persist much longer the agriculture department said wednesday 
rising costs brought on by drought are affecting livestock and 
poultry producers returns the departments economic research 
service said also poor pasture and range conditions are 
reducing forage supplies for cattle and lamb producers 
the report added if the drought continues hog and cattle 
slaughter may be boosted adding to alreadyrecord red meat and 
poultry supplies 
market prices of cattle dropped in june following record high 
levels during the spring and likely resulted in part from large 
meat supplies the report said 
feeder cattle prices weakened in response to lower fed cattle 
prices and rising feed costs it said while lower feeder 
cattle prices reduce returns to cowcalf producers the more 
immediate problem is poor pasture and water conditions 
although hay cut from land idled under federal programs has 
helped there will be more pressure to reduce the cattle inventory 
if pastures continue to deteriorate the report said 
total production of red meat and poultry in 1988 is expected to 
rise 3 percent to a record 599 billion pounds but all of the gain 
will be from pork lamb and mutton and poultry 
beef production this year was forecast at 229 billion pounds 
down 2 percent from last year 
