<TEXT>
recent staff additions at the national 
institutes of health have reduced the chance that potentially 
helpful new aids drugs could be overlooked a top health official 
told congress wednesday 
dr anthony s fauci coordinator of aids research for all of 
the federal institutes said we feel we will be able to mount a 
good effort with the staff now available 
fauci who also heads the national institute of allergy and 
infectious diseases had acknowledged under congressional 
questioning in spring that reviews of some requests for approval of 
drug studies was delayed by staff shortages 
vice president george bush quoted fauci last month as saying 
money approved for aids research activities at the institutes is 
about right 
which is right demanded sen edward m kennedy chairman of 
the senate labor and human resources committee 
fauci replied that both were that he received additional hiring 
authority soon after the spring hiring that has allowed him to 
recruit 20 additional reseachers for the remainder of the current 
budget year and allow him to add 19 more during the fiscal year 
that starts oct 1 
but even with additional manpower to handle more research fauci 
cautioned against raising expectations for substantial advances on 
aids treatment drugs or vaccines 
he agreed with food and drug commissioner frank young who 
testified earlier that the overwhelming majority of potential 
drugs that someone might consider useful are ruled out in the 
preliminary stages of actual testing 
young for example noted that the late actor rock hudson who 
died of aids went to france to obtain an unapproved drug that many 
people with the disease believed effective 
that drug is not looked at now as a promising drug young 
said pointing out that preliminary tests in the united states 
demonstrated that it was not really effective 
fauci said researchers walk a thin line between exploring every 
avenue for an effective drug and giving proper time to those that 
are most promising he told kennedy that nih researchers give 
consideration to approving studies if there is even a reasonable 
chance the drug will prove safe and effective 
but he said many get touted in newspapers that do not meet 
that standard 
the public might get misled when it reads in newspapers that a 
drug is promising said fauci 
the nih is responsible for approving clinical testing of new 
drugs where federal money is involved and works with the fda in 
developing testing protocals the fda has final authority on 
whether to approve a new drug for marketing or for widespread 
distribution just short of full market approval 
although nearly 40 drugs or combinations of possible aids drugs 
are in various stages of study none has shown enough promise to 
warrant their developers to apply to the fda for market approval 
