about 2500 workers went on strike 
wednesday at yugoslavias largest steel mill to protest drastic 
wage cuts and other government austerity measures the official 
news agency tanjug reported 
employees working at blast furnaces walked out in the early 
morning hours in protest of low pay in july tanjug said it gave 
no details 
communist party leaders worried about increasing social 
tensions also warned protesters not to demand radical change in 
the political system 
the steel mill employs about 18000 workers in this central 
yugoslav town it was built after world war ii and served as a 
symbol of communist industrial development until it began losing 
money in recent years 
many strikes have taken place since the government introduced an 
economic program in may that combined substantial price hikes and 
pay reductions the austerity measures spurred a further decline in 
living standards which have fallen by at least onethird since 
1980 
austerity plans worked out with the international monetary fund 
are intend to curb annual inflation of 175 percent and help 
yugoslavia repay its 21 billion foreign debt by making the economy 
more marketoriented 
the communist party presidium said the country has no 
alternative but to continue the austerity program despite 
widespread protests workers discontent does not have only a 
social background but also a very visible political component 
said a statement carried wednesday by official media 
it also warned against increasingly open clashes between 
leaderships of different yugoslav republics and provinces and the 
resulting public demonstrations the presidium said workers 
problems should be solved within their factories rather than in the 
streets 
workers have held several protest marches to air airing their 
grievances about the austerity measures and alleged corruption in 
the leadership they have chanted such slogans as down with 
communism and down with the government 
they also have demanded free elections independent trade unions 
and the curbing of privileges accorded party officials 
thousands of workers from a large shoe factory stormed the 
parliament building in belgrade last week 
yugoslavia had a record 1600 strikes last year involving 
300000 workers 
