state regulators filed formal charges of 
misrepresentation wednesday against an insurance company that sold 
1500 iowa farmers policies covering this years drought 
insurance commissioner william hager said farmers paid an 
average of 1000 each when they applied for the coverage but the 
company issued only four of the policies he did not estimate the 
total value of the policies 
hager said he would try to force the company federal insurance 
co to live up to the terms of the policies it sold or force it 
to return double the premiums farmers paid he added that he might 
seek civil penalties which could range up to 50000 
insurance commissioners in minnesota indiana and ohio have said 
theyre investigating the drought insurance policies the company a 
subsidiary of the chubb group insurance cos of warren nj wrote 
this year 
officials in minnesota and indiana warned that chubb could lose 
its license to do business in those states if if did not provide 
the coverage 
a group of 42 neighboring farmers in tennessee and kentucky 
demanded on tuesday that the company honor 3 million in drought 
policies that they bought 
chubb group spokeswoman mary lu korkuch said wednesday the 
company is working with state insurance commissioners to develop 
solutions 
the company she said had set aside 30 million to cover the 
drought policies and had reached that amount of coverage before the 
june 15 cutoff date for purchase of the insurance 
chubb officials met wednesday with michigan insurance bureau 
officials in lansing to explain that one of federals agents had 
violated his authority and with the help of unlicensed agents 
sold at least 9000 policies thousands more than the company had 
approved 
its one of the most bizarre scenarios ive ever seen 
its like science fiction said eric nordman director of 
property and liability for the michigan bureau 
it seems that one agent who developed a computer program for 
weather predictions went amok and had lots of unlicensed people 
selling insurance on his behalf nordman said 
the drought insurance policies designed to pay damages for 
abnormally low rainfall were advertised in iowa in early june when 
this years drought was worsening 
its pretty predictable they would have a significant number 
of applications hager said im not sure fraud is part of this 
situation i doubt whether there was a clear understanding of the 
level of interest in these policies 
the company hager said directed its agents to solicit as many 
policies as possible when it it knew or should have known that 
the company lacked adequate financial resources and reinsurance to 
write all of the coverage solicited 
the insurance coverage was marketed as drought insurance but 
the product in question is actually a weather policy whereby 
benefits are based solely on the amount of rainfall in a given 
area between june 1 and aug 31 
it has nothing to do with crop yields hager said 
a hearing on the administrative charges has been set for july 
25 hager said regulators in indiana have set a hearing for the 
following day 
