<TEXT>
the house was urged wednesday to improve its 
protection against terrorist attack by installing bomb detectors 
and requiring use of computerized identity cards to gain access to 
capitol office buildings 
an estimated 2450000 in interim security measures were 
recommended by house sergeant at arms jack russ who said that 
our system today can be defeated and wed like to make it 
tougher 
russ told a house administration subcommittee that installing 14 
bomb detectors in the capitol and at heavily used entrances to 
house office buildings would help counter a major security threat 
posed by plastic explosives 
he said plastic explosives can pass undiscovered through the 
current system of airportstyle metal detectors used in the capitol 
and adjacent office buildings 
russ estimated that conversion to computerized access cards for 
house members and employees entering office buildings from 
underground parking garages would cost an initial 2 million he 
proposed an eventual extension of the pass system to all 
congressional offices at an additional cost of 10 million 
the bomb detectors would cost an estimated 450000 and could be 
combined with existing metal detectors to screen one person every 
six seconds he said 
the subcommittee told russ to proceed immediately with another 
plan to switch from special license plates to automobile bumper 
stickers for house members and staff aides but deferred action on 
his other proposals 
rep joseph m gaydos dpa questioned the wisdom of making 
piecemeal improvements to the capitols security system and said 
the house should hire a team of outside experts to do a 
comprehensive study of security requirements 
russ responded that several such studies already had been 
conducted but that congressional leaders have rejected many 
recommendations such as erecting a wrought iron fence around the 
capitol grounds in the interest of maintaining easy access by 
visitors 
this is not like the kremlin agreed rep leon panetta 
dcalif the panel chairman the capitol of the united states 
and its offices represent a free democratic society and there are 
those who believe we cant turn the capitol into a fort 
russ said most of his proposals wednesday could be financed from 
13 million in unused funds previously appropriated by the house 
for security precautions 
several subcommittee members expressed doubts about improving 
security in the house without cooperation from the senate the 
senate side is like a different city russ replied if we 
waited for the senate to catch up with us wed never get anything 
done they march to a different drummer than we do 
the proposals russ advanced wednesday are the first step toward 
a more ambitious 185 million security plan that house leaders 
are still studying that plan also includes an emergency telephone 
system for alerting members immediately to any terrorist attack 
bombproof glass shields in the house visitors gallery and 
strengthening floor seats in the chamber to protect them against 
bomb blasts 
