<TEXT>
the state board of education voted 
wednesday to require emergency exit windows on new school buses 
the first design changes ordered since a fiery bus crash killed 27 
people in may 
the board also voted to require new buses to be powered by 
diesel fuel which is considered safer and less combustible than 
gasoline officials said that change had been proposed as an 
economy measure before the may 14 crash of the bus owned by the 
radcliff first assembly of god church which was gaspowered 
in addition to the changes the board ordered studies of other 
safety devices including roof exits additional side doors extra 
fire extinguishers and fireretardant seat covers 
the decisions followed the recommendations of a standing 
advisory committee that annually reviews the states bus safety 
standards 
sam jackson the state education departments representative on 
the advisory committee stressed that better training of drivers 
and evacuation training for school children may do more than the 
design measures 
pushout windows or any emergency exit are not worth a darn 
unless you develop some plan of evacuation jackson said 
but he added we definitely feel pushout windows will not 
hurt 
about twothirds of kentuckys school buses are gaspowered 
said byron watkins a committee member and assistant superintendent 
of hopkins county schools 
the state board also recommended that local districts 
restrict seating to two children per bench seat on buses making 
extracurricular trips and use separate vehicles to transport cargo 
such as band instruments and sports equipment children were 
sitting three abreast on the radcliff bus a capacity for which the 
bus was built 
step up busdriver training programs in defensive driving bus 
cleanliness evacuation and use of emergency equipment 
the radcliff churchs 1977 model bus exploded in flames when it 
was struck headon by a pickup truck driven in the wrong direction 
on interstate 71 near carrollton 
the victims who included 24 children were returning from an 
outing at the kings island amusement park near cincinnati the 
state medical examiner said all died of smoke inhalation not from 
crash injuries 
like school buses commonly in use in kentucky the church bus 
had a single emergency exit at the rear safety officials have said 
that was insufficient to evacuate a large numbers of passengers 
under the new rule the largest school buses those built for 
65 to 71 passengers must have two window exits on each side 
buses built for 35 to 53 passengers must have one window exit on 
each side 
buses equipped for the handicapped would need one window exit on 
35passenger models and two window exits on 65passenger models 
no additional exits would be required on any bus carrying 21 or 
fewer passengers 
the board also recommended but did not require that school 
systems install exit windows on existing buses that are used for 
trips outside local school districts 
kentucky has about 7500 school buses of which 1047 were built 
before 1978 when stricter federal safety standards went into 
effect said jackson those federal standards require a steel cage 
around the fuel tank a feature the radcliff bus lacked 
