the army corps of engineers wednesday began 
shipping fresh water from new orleans to plaquemines parish at the 
southern tip of the mississippi delta where river water has become 
too salty to drink 
salty gulf of mexico water has been creeping up the mississippi 
for weeks because the drought has reduced the rivers southern flow 
drastically 
the corps is drawing fresh water from the river at new orleans 
and shipping it on barges to pointe a la hache and other 
plaquemines communities corps spokesman bruce sossaman said the 
first barges should reach pointe a la hache by early thursday 
morning 
we anticipate delivering about 3 million gallons of water a 
day said don clement acting director of operations for the 
corps new orleans district 
if the salt water wedge migrates up well provide the same 
type of a service to the other parishes as their salt content 
increases clement told a gathering of state and local officials 
here 
the corps also is constructing an underwater sill near myrtle 
grove in plaquemines parish to impede the flow of salt water 
upriver the salt water is heavier than fresh water and creeps 
along the river bottom 
at the plaquemines parish intakes salt concentrations have been 
reported at more than 1500 parts per million 
health officials say salt cannot be tasted in concentrations 
below 400 or 500 parts per million and doesnt pose a health threat 
until it reaches 1000 parts per million or more 
