<DOCNO> AP880713-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an expert business witness in court cases states 
that the personnel files of many corporations are crammed with 
explosives so unstable they can blow up with little agitation 
such files says eugene jennings should be purged since those 
explosions are occurring with growing frequency and could be 
extremely costly in terms of dollars and reputations 
the files to which jennings refers are those containing 
evaluations of officers performances based on subjective and 
interpretive criteria rather than hard factual information 
increasingly he says officers are suing fellow officers for 
tortious a tort is a legal term for a wrongful or injurious civil 
act interference with their economic relationship to the employer 
as a confidential counselor to top executives and corporations 
jennings is most concerned about those instances in which officers 
make unfair improper or unreasonable judgments about another 
officers performance and career 
while complete data is difficult to come by partly because most 
suits are settled out of court jennings says that 26 such 
complaints were filed in new york state in 1986 and 15 in 
massachusetts last year 
for many years jennings a management professor at michigan 
state university has helped corporations set forth theories 
enabling them to defend themselves against such suits based on 
established criteria used by many companies 
but today he states such practices carry less weight no 
matter how commonly used this is especially so he says if the 
evaluation criteria are based on such interpretative and subjective 
items as common sense good judgment ambition and loyalty 
these are what jennings derisively calls uub an acronym for 
unintelligent undefinable babble 
nothing will cause a corporate case to fall apart than to use 
such undescriptive words as leadership motivation originality and 
style nobody defines them in the same way he says 
jennings says he is finding it more difficult to lay out a 
businesss defense in such suits 
he cites this actual example for nine years mr x an 
executive received all 10s on performance the result of 
subjective interpretive categories a new boss was named 
suddenly mr x received 9s and 8s and then 7s 
among other things lawyers for mr x learned on examination 
that the new boss interpreted leadership to mean discipline while 
the old boss held to the belief that it meant motivation on just 
what was mr x being rated 
the term motivation causes all sorts of trouble in a certain 
case one officerboss maintained that motivation meant making 
people work harder while another said it was to make them feel 
better 
so vague are the terms even to those using them says jennings 
that in another case corporate officers rehearsed consistent 
definitions prior to examination in court to their humiliation 
their ploy was uncovered 
in the past says jennings corporations believed that officers 
did not come under rules that apply to other employees 
particularly regarding discrmination and especially discrimination 
of women and minorities 
but says jennings all human beings come under a rule that 
nobody can interfere unreasonably and improperly with the economic 
relationship between an employee and employer 
he contends that when subjective criteria are used it is an 
invitation for ingrained conscious and unconscious biases to 
come into play even when applied without discriminatory intent 
for such reasons he says a trend is developing among 
corporations to clear up the evaluation process among other 
things it means getting rid of standard forms says jennings who 
is helping companies make changes 
a technique jennings recommends is to have a superior and 
subordinate agree at the start of each year what must be done in 
the job what reasonable resources must be utilized and what 
timeframe is needed for results 
at the end of the year says jennings the subordinate is 
evaluated strictly on these criteria thus making the performance 
evaluation detailed objective and activitybased 
he concedes that such a technique might not always be possible 
then he says it is far better that a performance evaluation be as 
general as possible as to the subordinate officers 
responsibilities 
it can be as general as this mr y is in charge of corporate 
public relations and so is expected to fulfill all the duties that 
normally are associated with this activity by reasonable and proper 
methods 
while it may not be as effective as the annual conferencetype 
evaluation jennings believes the general format is far less 
hurtful in a legal sense than if subjective interpretive critieria 
are used 
again he warns companies to beware of subjective criteria in 
selecting promoting or rewarding individuals he suggests that if 
they have been doing so they should purge their files and begin 
again 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

