<TEXT>
as the new president of the united methodist 
council of bishops bishop ernest t dixon jr says that no matter 
how impressive the institution or exalted the position hes 
regarded primarily as black 
thats what identifies you he says your blackness 
hes not brooding about it or critical but simply talking 
plainly about a seemingly intractable and restrictive reality 
a genial lanky man who laughs easily dixon first encountered 
that aberration in himself in reverse as a youth but says he 
outgrew it it still pigeonholes him though he says in its 
narrowlensed way 
youre considered first of all not a human being not a 
christian not a bishop but a black im not ashamed of it but it 
hurts sometimes 
its the ingrained slanted attitude toward blacks of a 
predominantly white society even though it ostensibly rejects 
racism dixon says and he notes that it comes up in all sorts of 
incidental ways 
even in my present position folks dont ever let you forget 
you are different he said in an interview at the denominations 
recent governing conference in st louis 
youre a black bishop people dont refer to white bishops 
as white but to black bishops as black i dont think its 
intentional but people come up and say oh youre one of our 
black bishops 
dixon 65 of san antonio texas chief ecclesiastical leader of 
the mainly white denomination of nearly 10 million for the 198889 
term has a special understanding of racial bias because he once 
shared some of it 
i gained some insight into white americanss stereotyping of 
black persons from experience in my early years he said a rangy 
man with whispyhaired balding head he squinted his eyes in 
reminiscence 
he said that in his youth in san antonio where he now heads the 
church mexicans used to be put down below blacks 
i used to hear my father and grandfather talk about mexican 
sharecroppers as shiftless and irresponsibile going off and 
leaving their crops 
i had some stereotypes myself i hadnt had the opportunity to 
associate with mexicans as my peers i hadnt reflected on how they 
were rejected then the kind of places they had to live how they 
were deprived of education 
not until you grow up does one break free of the baseless 
stereotyping dixon said your attitude changes at least it 
should he said although blacks still are often lumped as blacks 
rather than seen as individuals 
however among his churchs approximately 100 bishops over which 
he now presides he said i think we have achieved a degree of 
respect and collegiality that enables us to work together 
yet we constantly have to monitor each other to keep black 
bishops from being oversensitive and keep white bishops from being 
patronizing 
dixon succeeds bishop earl g hunt jr of lakeland fla 
asked what should be the main emphasis of a denomination that 
has lost nearly 2 million members in the last 22 years dixon said 
i would hope were moving in a new direction focused on our 
local congregations on equipping the saints our efforts must be 
to strengthen and revitalize the local church and also start new 
congregations 
he said a long sequence of events previously had absorbed 
denominational energies social justice causes and organizational 
restructuring 
the whole idea of evangelism became almost abandoned he 
said but its now in the forefront we need more biblical 
preaching more study of the bible in small groups 
congregations that are rooted in scripture with an 
opportunity to be involved in bible study those churches are 
growing at the same time we must also have christian outreach 
ministries of community service 
you cant preach jesus christ and him crucified without 
dealing with basic social issues of feeding the hungry and caring 
for the dispossessed 
dixon did his early church service under racial segregation he 
led small black congregations directed extension training of 
rural negro ministers at alabamas tuskeegee institute oversaw 
black christian education in texas 
afterward he worked for the national churchs local church 
division later headed philander smith college in little rock 
ark before joining the denominations program council in dayton 
ohio in 1969 
that was just one year after the denomination integrated its 
separate black jurisdiction with whites elected a bishop in 1972 
dixon served in topeka kan until 1980 when he shifted to san 
antonio 
