<DOCNO> AP880713-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fifteen years ago a young physically leaner 
spiritually meaner jesse louis jackson told a black audience his 
perception of a harsh truth i would not run for president of the 
united states he said because white people are incapable of 
appreciating me 
it was a statement that spoke volumes if not about the state of 
race relations at the time about the state of jesse jackson and 
what drove this selfstyled country preacher and prodigal 
lieutenant of the late martin luther king jr to change his mind 
now even in defeat he ranks as perhaps the most electrifying 
presidential candidate since robert f kennedy 
burning within him by the account of relatives childhood 
friends and not a few enemies is a nearly lifelong fear of 
rejection and thus an obsessive urge to test his worthiness some 
think it was borne only partly by the bitter shock of racial 
bigotry in his native greenville sc and perhaps more profoundly 
by his vivid memory of childhood taunts from white and black kids 
alike jessee aint got no daddee jessee aint got no 
daddee 
white america jackson acknowledges has matured since he 
uttered his cynical appraisal in 1973 of political and racial 
reality but so has jesse jackson step by tentative painful step 
from turtlenecks and bellbottoms to christian dior and pinstripes 
from street poetry in new york to delicate diplomacy in syria from 
the embrace of fidel castro to the tearful cradling of a young 
quadriplegic girl who cheered him in an allwhite community in 
oregon 
four years ago as others still insisted that no black could win 
the white house and especially not a black preacher with no prior 
political experience jackson claimed even in his most private 
candid moments that he could his formula was a rainbow 
coalition of new black voters in the south other minorities 
women of all races white liberals unemployed bluecollar workers 
and depressed farmers 
the rainbow never materialized and in 1984 jackson finished a 
distant third behind walter mondale and gary hart for the 
democratic nomination rarely pulling more than 3 percent of the 
white vote in any state even so it was the mst dramatic showing 
by any black in the history of presidential politics and all the 
more remarkable in light of his own misadventures 
he had his triumphs in that campaign to be sure not the least 
his mushrooming success in leading young people by the sheer power 
of his oratory from the temptation of drugs he negotiated the 
release from syria of navy lt robert goodman shot down in a raid 
over lebanon he enrolled upwards of 2 million new democratic 
voters making the difference by some accounts in the partys 
recapture of the senate in 1986 
but jacksons campaign organization was a shambles largely the 
result of his scattershot impulsive scheduling and his refusal to 
delegate authority raising questions about his ability to run a 
government and rekindling criticism of the administrative 
irregularities which marked his stewardship of earlier enterprises 
particularly operation push his chicagobased civil rights 
organization 
worse jackson alienated party professionals by whining about 
the delegateselection rules hinting as he often has when 
something goes against him that they were designed to shut him out 
because of race he infuriated americans jews by making a crack 
about hymies and hymietown and by his lessthandamning 
response to the behavior of campaign supporter louis farrakhan the 
black moslem leader who called adolf hitler wickedly great 
humbled by those mistakes though slow to admit them publicly 
jackson brought tears to the eyes of democratic convention 
delegates in san francisco in the 1984 when he intoned 
if in my low moments in word deed or attitude through some 
error of temper taste or tone i have caused anyone discomfort 
created pain or revived someones fears that was not my truest 
self i am not a perfect servant i am a public servant doing my 
best against the odds as i develop and serve be patient god is 
not finished with me yet 
he promised himself and his campaign loyalists that things 
would be different this year that he would be a positive force for 
the party that he would share authority with his staff and remain 
on the high road of human tolerance 
he has done all that winning high marks from even his 
staunchest opponents for grace on the campaign trail the effort 
was no more apparent than when jackson refused to be drawn into a 
bloodletting with new york mayor ed koch who endorsed sen albert 
gore jr of tennessee and declared jews would be crazy to vote 
for jackson 
for all his determination to give the country a more mature 
less contentious candidate this time jackson himself had no idea 
until a bitterly cold night in remotest iowa just how different 
things would be 
it was the night of the 1987 super bowl giants versus the 
broncos jackson was unhappy he figured everybody was settled in 
for the game so why was he being driven to greenfield 50 miles 
southwest of des moines in 15degree weather for a church 
appearance that surely should never have been scheduled 
on the edge of town jackson was dozing when the county sheriff 
stopped the car and shined his flashlight into jacksons face 
theyre here theyre here the officer shouted jackson was 
baffled the officer pointed to the cars parked at the side of the 
road more than a mile from the church an overflow crowd of 800 
people nearly all of them white had turned out 
it was a start of a new relationship with white america for 
jesse jackson one that took him from the coalmining hollows of 
kentucky to the coast of maine to the poolside chic of beverly 
hills to selma ala where the mayor acknowledged that he stood on 
the wrong side of the edmund pettus bridge on that bloody sunday 23 
years earlier and jackson could agree that it was time to forgive 
each other redeem each other and move on 
he would not sweep their votes but he made new friends reached 
new understandings he won half a dozen southern primaries 
caucuses in michigan and several other states and finished a 
respectable second in others including lilywhite maine vermont 
and minnesota not enough to wrest the nomination from 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis but enough to make himself the 
second strongest force to be reckoned with in the party enough to 
suggest though not demand that he be picked for the vice 
presidency 
with the presidential fight clearly over and the vice presidency 
out of his grasp jackson still stood proud and defiant 
i was born against the odds i survived against the odds 
im an oddsbreaker and a dreammaker and i will never surrender 
he said 
</TEXT>
