<TEXT>
certainly he was the most exciting candidate and the most 
enigmatic here was a fellow who has never held public office 
running for president never served in the military running for 
president a minister of the poor preaching the life of christ 
wearing designer suits pocketing a sixfigure income from 
appearance fees flying about in executive jets staying at the 
best hotels missing vast amounts of time from family yet 
sactifying family life and values an advocate of school busing and 
federal aid to public schools but who sent one son to one of the 
most exclusive private schools in washington a street poet who 
depending on the audience speaks ghetto gospel or ivy league 
like another powerful communicator ronald reagan jackson 
cloaks his ideas in anecdotes and aphorisms and has no trouble 
getting them on page 1 or the 6 oclock news some think there is 
more entertainer than intellectual in his rhymeandmime wizardry 
but he has an inventive mind and quickly synthesizes facts and 
figures then he smiles ive got to jesseize it 
thus a pitch for universal health insurance and day care comes 
out better day care and health care on the front side of life 
than jail care and welfare on the back side 
his agenda derives from three social movements civil rights 
peace and populism to which he adds as a preacher a strong dash 
of moralism on the subject of drugs and selfresponsibility a 
thousand times probably more he has brought audiences black and 
white to their feet by thundering 
brown black and white 
were all precious in gods sight 
i am somebody 
i am somebody 
the tone is one of moving on he says the era of racial violence 
has ended that now it is time to end economic violence and 
poverty he emphasizes comes in all colors to a group of 
distressed white farmers in the south he says to a roar of 
laughter and approval my friends when they foreclose on your 
farm and turn the lights out we all look amazingly alike in the 
dark 
it was only four years ago that jackson spun a different tune 
when he told audiences about what it was like growing up black in 
the south saturdays id sell peanuts and soft drinks at the 
stadium whites all around drinking liquor theyd say all kinds 
of vulgar things call me nigger try to shortchange me 
couldnt go to the front at the movies couldnt use the bathrooms 
it was humiliating 
and jacksons comfort or lack of it with whites has long 
been a source of concern with other black leaders including his 
mentor martin luther king even after king quickly elevated the 
bright young man who left theological school to join the southern 
christian leadership conference he didnt want jesse negotiating 
for him with white leaders giving that assignment instead to 
andrew young now mayor of atlanta 
to this day other black leaders from the sclc ranks regard 
jackson with some suspicion king himself complained about 
jacksons ego and at least once blew up over it in front of others 
at the root at least in part of jacksons problem with a 
number of other black leaders is the curious story he repeated time 
and again in the immediate wake of kings assassination perceived 
as an opportunistic and cynical attempt to leap over others to 
claim kings mantel 
after king was gunned down on the balcony of the lorraine motel 
in memphis in april 1968 jackson told reporters waiting at the 
hospital that he was the last man that king had talked to some 
reporters said that jackson also claimed he cradled the dying king 
in his arms that so incensed another king lieutenant hosea 
williams that williams physically attacked jackson on the hospital 
grounds i just jumped on jess because he was telling lies 
williams recalled in 1983 
making matters worse jackson left for chicago the night of the 
assassination wearing a turtleneck shirt stained with blood he 
told television viewers the blood was kings moreover he wore the 
same shirt for two more days and repeated the story on network 
interviews according to williams young and ralph david 
abernathy the story just wasnt true jesse was not on the 
balcony said young 
jackson now acknowledges he was not on the balcony and denies 
ever telling anyone differently as for being the last person to 
speak to king jackson says i was he was talking to me in the 
courtyard 
the harsh view is that he was and is a charlatan in pastors 
robes driven by ego flitting from one brushfire to another only 
long enough to get his face on the camera again even in high 
school his french teacher xanthene norris constantly lectured 
him about being an i person always an i person i am 
somebody thats jesse she said 
at the chicago theological seminary jackson nearly flunked 
preaching of all things because he wouldnt bother to write out 
his sermons in advance as the course required thats jesse 
said the rev victor obenhaus a retired professor who was 
jacksons faculty adviser 
but anyone who believes jacksons sole interest is 
selfaggrandizement likely hasnt spent much time with him his 
pace is simply too grueling takes him to too many backwaters too 
many slums and through too many sleepless nights to be explained 
away by ego alone he has the trait for sickle cell anemia yet 
pushes himself to the point that he has been hospitalized at least 
half a dozen times for exhaustion 
so what drives jesse jackson some say it is a true messianic 
fervor for the poor the minorities the locked out and some 
say it is a long underlying fear that he still isnt accepted 
being born out of wedlock bothered him disproportionatly to the 
way it did anyone else we grew up with said his halfbrother 
noah robinson humiliation thats the fuel that pushes jesse 
jackson says thats simplistic somebody elses romance of 
my life in an interview he said the discovery when he was 5 or 
6 years old that the father he was living with was not his natural 
father was interesting but it was not traumatic because i was 
never fatherless or an orphan 
yet when the adrenaline is running when he is in his pulpit 
jesse jackson has let it pour out in different terms to a 
different audience 
you are gods child when i was in my mothers belly i had no 
father to give me a name they called me bastard and rejected 
me you are somebody you are gods child 
</TEXT>
