<DOCNO> AP880713-0277 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
airlines tough security policies spawn cottage industry 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the airlines have been getting tough on air 
piracy with some outside help 
the rise in international terrorism in recent years and the 
heightened threat of hijacking has spawned a cottage industry of 
security companies providing passenger screening and other services 
under contract with the airlines 
security in the air has taken on a new sense of urgency in 
recent days following the shooting down of an iran air jetliner by 
a us navy warship in the persian gulf the nations big airlines 
that fly overseas arent taking any chances on a retaliatory 
hijacking and have beefed up their already tight security measures 
although the big carriers have their own security divisions 
their mounting work loads have prompted them to call on outside 
companies for help in stemming the rise in air violence 
airline security is an undertaking of great magnitude its a 
difficult assignment said dick lally assistant vice president 
for security at the air transport association a washingtonbased 
trade group that represents the nations major carriers 
since the federal government mandated 100 percent screening 
of airline passengers at the beginning of 1973 lally noted the 
major airlines have stepped up their security and refined their 
techniques and equipment many carriers have security standards 
tougher than the governments 
each year us airline and contract security agents uncover and 
seize 3000 to 4000 firearms and make around 1500 related 
arrests according to the air transport group the metal detectors 
and xray equipment used in the screening are already into their 
fourth generation 
it has become more efficient and costeffective in many cases 
for airlines to farm out security work rather than training more 
of their own staff to handle it in departure gate areas shared by 
several airlines it makes sense for a common passenger checkpoint 
to be located in the concourse leading to a gate area instead of 
each airline having its own security setup at every gate 
one of the airlines using the gate area usually assumes 
responsibility for the concourse checkpoint contracting with an 
outside security company and splitting the costs of the contract 
with the other airlines in that section 
the granddaddy of security companies whose clients include 
airlines is wackenhut corp which works for nearly all the major 
us carriers 
wackenhut has a high profile last february armed guards from 
the company were mobilized at kennedy international airport in new 
york by beleaguered pan am corp after teamsters union leaders 
vowed guerrilla warfare against the airline in a wage dispute 
we do get called by companies if theres labor unrest said 
patrick cannan a spokesman for wackenhut at its headquarters in 
coral gables fla 
beefy wackenhut guards also were in evidence at giant texas air 
corps annual shareholders meeting last month in new york frank 
lorenzo texas airs chairman threatened publicly several times to 
have the guards eject angry shareholders if they persisted in 
asking him questions after he had requested they stop 
wackenhut a publicly owned company has 28000 fulltime 
employees and is wellknown nationally but the handful of other 
security firms catering to airlines globe security systems inc 
jj security inc and ogden allied services corp are either 
privately held or subsidiaries of other companies 
some of the big us airlines that carry passengers overseas 
also hire local security firms in foreign nations 
in this country many of the bigger betterknown security 
companies had unhappy experiences and got out of airline work 
leaving the field to the smaller firms 
that airline security was a segment of business we werent 
interested in participating in any longer said joe allen a 
spokesman for baker industries inc parent of both wells fargo and 
burns international security services 
the two security subsidiaries stopped doing airline work about 
two or three years ago allen said mainly because of liability 
problems that could result from hijackings being blamed on 
inadequate security provided by the companies 
allen explained that the decision to get out of airline security 
work was accelerated by litigation arising from the crash of an air 
india jumbo jet in june 1985 burns which provided the passenger 
screening for the flight was named as a defendant by families of 
the victims in a case still in the courts the crash off the coast 
of ireland which killed all 329 people aboard was blamed on a 
bomb planted by sikh terrorists 
cpppinkertons another security giant has shied away from 
airline work for the past four to five years 
wackenhuts cannan conceded that liability for poor security can 
be a problem he stressed however that each security contract 
with the airlines is different and many of them provide for joint 
liability 
the airlines are sensitive about security many of them admit 
that they hire outside contractors but refuse to discuss any 
details or to disclose how much they spend on security 
four of the nations airlines pan am twa american and 
northwest levy a special security charge of 5 per ticket 
pan am like twa is one of the most securityconscious us 
airlines in addition to its internal security division and 
contracts with wackenhut pan ams world services subsidiary sells 
security maintenance and other services to government agencies and 
other airlines 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

