industries inc its largest shareholder to delay warners 118 
billion acquisition of lorimar telepictures corp 
chriscraft a broadcasting and manufacturing company filed the 
suit tuesday in new york state court 
in a statement issued wednesday warner denied chriscrafts 
claim that the merger with lorimar which owns six television 
stations would violate a 1984 agreement prohibiting warner from 
owning any tv station so long as it owns 25 percent or more of 
chriscrafts bhc inc broadcasting subsidiary 
warner has a 425 percent stake in bhc which it acquired from 
chriscraft in 1984 in exchange for a 23 percent interest in 
warners voting stock 
chriscrafts suit seeks to delay the completion of the merger 
until lorimar has sold its tv stations to an outside party or 
warner has transferred enough of its bhc stock so that it owns less 
than 25 percent of the unit 
warner has proposed putting the six lorimar stations in a voting 
trust but chriscraft maintained that would still violate the 1984 
agreement and cause injury to chriscraft 
warner said it intends to move forward to complete the merger 
which puts a value of about 14 on each of lorimars 47 million 
outstanding common shares for a total of around 630 million in 
addition warner plans to assume lorimars debt of about 550 
million 
chriscrafts four representatives on warners board of 
