<TEXT>
the us appetite for foreign oil increased 
sharply in the first half of the year while domestic crude 
production kept declining according to an industry report 
published wednesday 
the american petroleum institutes report showed us imports of 
crude oil and petroleum products jumped 141 percent in the first 
six months of the year from the same period in 1987 the nations 
total oil imports rose to an average 693 million barrels a day 
from 607 million barrels a year earlier 
a barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons 
the rising imports mean that 41 percent of the oil consumed in 
this country is now imported noted the monthly statistical report 
by the washingtonbased trade group 
the spike in imports in the first half was partly the result of 
differences in oil stocking between this year and 1987 the report 
said it nevertheless continues a very disturbing trend towards 
increased reliance on foreign sources of petroleum for our basic 
energy needs said edward h murphy director of the groups 
finance accounting and statistics department 
domestic crude production on the other hand slipped 23 
percent during the januaryjune period to an average 82 million 
barrels a day the report blamed the production decline largely on 
the fall in world oil prices since 1986 which it said has pushed 
crude prices 40 percent lower than before the slide 
the decline in crude output has been partly offset by a slow but 
steady increase in alaskan production as a result of projects 
planned many years ago coming onstream in the past two years 
