<TEXT>
a member of the house agriculture committee 
said wednesday he will introduce legislation expanding the 
jurisdiction of the commodity futures trading commission to cover 
stock index options 
the measure being drafted by rep glenn english dokla would 
transfer authority to the cftc that is now held by the securities 
and exchange commission 
word of the proposal gave a new twist to congressional tinkering 
with the way the government oversees the nations financial 
markets it also illustrated the turf fights that have erupted in 
congress over the issue since the financial markets crash last 
october 
until now most of the attention on capitol hill has been 
focused on a bill introduced july 7 by rep edward markey dmass 
that would move things in the opposite direction markeys proposal 
would shift jurisdiction over stock index futures contracts from 
the cftc to the securities and exchange commission 
markey is chairman of the house telecommunications and finance 
subcommittee which oversees the sec the agency that regulates the 
nations stock exchanges and most options transactions many 
members of house and senate committees that oversee the sec have 
argued that to improve regulation of the nations financial 
markets the sec should be given expanded powers 
the agriculture committee oversees the cftc the regulator of 
the futures markets members of the house and senate agriculture 
panels have sought to defend the cftcs jurisdiction 
at a hearing of the house agriculture committee on wednesday 
english noted that after the october crash the sec received far 
more complaints from investors than did the cftc the sec has 
reported receiving 620 letters and 9360 telephone calls from 
midoctober thru late november with complaints while the cftc says 
it has logged three complaints about the crash 
you have one regulator doing a very good job and another 
where all the complaints occurred that hasnt appeared to be 
doning a very good job english said 
the lawmaker said that if regulatory powers are to be 
consolidated perhaps we ought to unify in the direction from 
which were getting the least public complaints 
